{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
<h1>Kernel & Request Lifecycle</h1>
<p>
    The <code>Kernel</code> is the core of Rhapsody's request handling. It orchestrates
    the entire request lifecycle from receiving a <code>Request</code> to returning a <code>Response</code>.
</p>

<h2>Kernel Responsibilities</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Handling</strong> – Routes the request and executes middleware.</li>
    <li><strong>Termination</strong> – Performs post-response tasks like injecting the debug toolbar.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Handle Phase</h2>
<p>
    <code>Kernel::handle()</code> is a pure function: Request in, Response out.
    It delegates to <code>Router::dispatch()</code> and normalizes 404/500 status codes
    into <code>HttpException</code> for consistent error handling.
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">$response = $kernel->handle($request);</code></pre>

<h2>The Terminate Phase</h2>
<p>
    <code>Kernel::terminate()</code> performs post-response tasks that don't affect
    the meaning of the response:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Injects the development debug toolbar.</li>
    <li>Adds framework update notifications.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    This method is safe to skip entirely (e.g., in production, or for non-HTML responses).
</p>

<h2>Error Handling</h2>
<p>
    <code>HttpException</code> is intentionally allowed to propagate out of <code>handle()</code>
    uncaught. The global <code>ErrorHandler</code> (registered in <code>index.php</code>)
    owns turning it into a rendered error page.
</p>

<h2>Example Usage</h2>
<pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Kernel;
use Rhapsody\Core\Request;

$kernel = new Kernel($container, $config);
$request = new Request();

try {
    $response = $kernel->handle($request);
    $response = $kernel->terminate($request, $response);
    $response->send();
} catch (HttpException $e) {
    // ErrorHandler handles this globally
    throw $e;
}</code></pre>

<h2>Testing</h2>
<p>
    The pure nature of <code>Kernel::handle()</code> makes it easy to test:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">$kernel = new Kernel($container, $config);
$request = new Request();

$response = $kernel->handle($request);
$this->assertEquals(200, $response->getStatusCode());</code></pre>

<h2>Request Lifecycle Summary</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Environment loaded (<code>.env</code>)</li>
    <li>Error handler registered</li>
    <li>Session started</li>
    <li>Container built</li>
    <li>Routes loaded</li>
    <li><strong>Kernel::handle()</strong> – middleware & controller executed</li>
    <li><strong>Kernel::terminate()</strong> – debug toolbar & banners injected</li>
    <li>Response sent to client</li>
</ol>
{% endblock %}